In TypeScript, you can use type assertions to explicitly specify the type of a variable or expression, even if TypeScript's type inference or narrowing algorithms cannot infer the exact type. This can be useful when you know that a value has a specific type in practice, even if it could theoretically have multiple types.

Here's an example:

```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
}

interface Admin {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  role: string;
}

function isAdmin(user: User | Admin): user is Admin {
  return (user as Admin).role !== undefined;
}

const user: User | Admin = { id: 1, name: "John Doe", role: "admin" };

if (isAdmin(user)) {
  const admin: Admin = user as Admin; // type assertion
  console.log(admin.role);
} else {
  const userWithoutRole: Omit<User, "role"> = user; // type narrowing
  console.log(userWithoutRole.name);
}
```

In this example, we have a `User` and `Admin` interface with some overlapping properties. We define a function `isAdmin` that takes a `User` or `Admin` and returns a boolean indicating whether the user is an `Admin`.

We then have a variable `user` that can be either a `User` or an `Admin`. We use the `isAdmin` function to check whether `user` is an `Admin`, and if so, we use a type assertion to explicitly specify that `user` is an `Admin` and assign it to a variable `admin`.

If `user` is not an `Admin`, we use type narrowing to remove the `role` property from the `User` type and assign it to a variable `userWithoutRole`.

By using type assertions and narrowing, we can tell the TypeScript type system that we know the exact type of a value, even if it could theoretically have multiple types. This can help improve type safety and reduce the number of type errors in our code.

